{"entry_type":"decision","summary":"Notification system uses event-driven architecture via EventBus exclusively, with pluggable NotificationAdapter interface for delivery channels","detail":"EventBus is already the primary communication pattern in the codebase (OrderService uses it for order:created). It supports async handlers, provides an event log for debugging/testing, and enables loose coupling. The adapter pattern on top allows adding new channels (email, webhook, SMS) without modifying the core service. All notifications must flow through EventBus.emit() and be delivered through NotificationAdapter implementations.","tags":["architecture"],"scope":"src/","agent_id":"agent-1","id":"01KN8DVREY76F3FP08KKPM1J0V","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:03:31.806Z"}
{"entry_type":"constraint","summary":"All notification triggers must go through EventBus.emit() — no direct service calls or CallbackRegistry for notifications","detail":"The notification system uses event-driven architecture exclusively. Domain services (OrderService, UserService, etc.) emit typed events via EventBus. NotificationService subscribes to those events and delegates delivery to registered NotificationAdapter implementations. The CallbackRegistry pattern is no longer used for notifications. To add a new notification trigger: 1) Define the event type in src/events/event-types.ts, 2) Emit it from the relevant service, 3) Add a handler in NotificationService.","tags":["architecture","notification"],"scope":"src/","agent_id":"agent-1","id":"01KN8E3CDKBH5C9K81YW09MA0F","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:07:41.619Z"}
